draw(graph(f,-.7,2.7),linewidth(1),Arrows(6));
[/asy]

chosen:
We begin by simplifying the left side of the equation:
\begin{align*}
|x + y - 1| + \Big| |x| - x \Big| + \Big| |x - 1| + x - 1 \Big| &= |x + y - 1| + |x - x| + ||x - 1| - (x - 1)| \\
&= |x + y - 1| + 0 + | |x - 1| - (x - 1)| \\
&= |x + y - 1| + |x - 1 - (x - 1)| \\
&= |x + y - 1| + 0 \\
&= |x + y - 1|.
\end{align*}Hence, the equation becomes $|x + y - 1| = 0,$ which we can rewrite as $|x + y - 1| = 0.$

Thus, the graph of the equation is just a line segment along the line $y = 1 - x.$

Furthermore, since the absolute value signs are always non-negative, the left-hand side of the equation will be 0 only when the inside of each absolute value is zero.  This means that $x = 1,$ $|x| = x,$ and $|x - 1| = x - 1.$  In other words, the only possible values for $x$ are $0$ and $1.$  Hence, the graph is the line segment between $(0,1)$ and $(1,0),$ which has length $\boxed{\sqrt{2}}.$

[asy]
unitsize (2 cm);

pair A, B, O;

O = (0,0);
A = (1,0);
B = (0,1);

draw((-1.2,0)--(1.2,0));
draw((0,-1.2)--(0,1.2));

draw(O--A--B--cycle);

dot("$A$", A, SE);
dot("$B$", B, NW);

label("$1$", (1.2,0), S);
label("$1$", (0,1.2), E);

label("$x$", (0.5,0), S);
label("$y$", (0,0.5), W);
[/asy]
Therefore, the answer is $\boxed{\sqrt{2}}$.

